    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Student loans are often calculated using the \"average daily balance\" method, which can make the principal reduction feel sluggish at first. When you make a payment, a portion goes toward accrued interest, and only the remainder reduces the actual principal balance. This means that in the early months, a significant chunk of your payment is \"eaten\" by interest, so the principal balance barely shrinks. It is entirely normal for the principal to remain relatively stable for the first few years before the interest portion of your payment decreases significantly. Once the interest rate drops below your payment amount, you'll start seeing the principal balance decrease more rapidly.\n\nThink of it like a small, very efficient, and very hungry goblin in your house. This goblin is eating all the food you bring home every night, leaving almost nothing for you to save. The goblin is the interest, and it is very good at hiding its true hunger by making you feel like you've done nothing wrong. You might think you are saving the food, but the goblin is eating it all. Eventually, the goblin gets tired and stops eating as much, and then you start saving more. You will feel like nothing is happening at first, but eventually, you will start to",
