    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to feel frustrated, and while the interest calculation is standard, there are a few specific factors that can slow down your progress even if you are paying more than the minimum. First, the \"accrued interest\" method means any extra payment you make might get applied to the interest portion first if the system hasn't updated the balance yet, though most lenders automatically apply extras to principal. Second, if you have multiple loans with different interest rates, your extra payment might be getting applied to the loan with the lowest rate first, leaving your highest-rate loans to fester. Finally, late fees or administrative processing delays from the lender can sometimes temporarily stall your principal reduction if payments aren't posted correctly on time.\n\nTo speed things up, always confirm exactly which loan your extra payment hits and consider making a larger lump sum payment once a year rather than small monthly additions, as this can have a compounding effect on the balance reduction. It is also worth checking if your loan has any \"forbearance\" or \"deferment\" statuses attached, as these can pause your progress entirely. While the system is designed to be efficient, it is not a goblin; it is just a math problem that requires a little more strategy to",
      "source": "target",
